metadata.name: Plottable Era: (II) Medieval #124
metadata.description:
'Plottable Era: (II) Medieval' is the second generator in the "Era" generators series, highlighting different periods and civilizations. Following "Primitive", this new series shows epic battle in a medieval scenery with mountains, castles, and ships.

Each NFT is a recipe to a physical plot (A4) and utilizes the Redeemables feature of fxhash, allowing owners to unlock a physical plot directly coming from @greweb's pen plotter.

The NFT serves as the key to obtaining a physically plottable art piece. It exports an SVG file that can be used for plotting with pens. Plotter artists have the freedom to utilize their own materials and ship the completed artwork to collectors, provided they possess the NFT at the time of the request. To obtain the .SVG file, simply drag and drop it into a folder or right-click and save.

For those interested in the technical details, this work was created using WebGL + Rust + WASM and is licensed under CC BY-SA 4.0. Additional information and the source code for this piece can be found at this link: https://github.com/gre/gre/tree/master/doodles/plottable-era-medieval

metadata.name: RULES (for Elementary Cellular Automata) #29
metadata.description:
An important element of generative art is emergence. The most famous algorithm for this is probably Cellular Automata (CA).

However, numerous generative artists have created works using CA, which has lost its visual freshness and is like chewing gum that has lost its taste.

Although it is such a classic algorithm, adding my own little ideas to it and finding a new "flavor" is the reason why I code.

Here, the subject is 1D Elementary Cellular Automata, the simplest of all cellular automata. 1D Elementary Cellular Automata has 256 different rules, which change the shapes produced. This work aims to create more complex shapes by randomly selecting some of those rules and placing multiple of them on the screen.

The on/off of the CA cell is often likened to the behavior of living creatures.As of 2022, in the country where I live, prices are rising, wages are not increasing, and COVID-19 has not yet ended. I created this work with the image of people at the mercy of these various rules.

---

Screen click: Change rules
S key: Save png
L key: Show/hide grid

metadata.name: Butterflies #49
metadata.description:
The Butterflies token is another in a series of tokens of a larger project called Kim Blood 2024. It is a total collection of digital "postage" stamps with various themes.
The tokens from this series available on fx(hash) are a combination of generatively layered pngs and a procedurally rendered barcode in a transparent image cutout.
While the individual layers are repeated with varying rarity in various rare combinations, the generated barcode is unique for each mintage.

Individual generatively layered pngs:
1. Handcrafted frame with serrations of stamps in nine color versions. These color versions are set with different rarity in a 1:1:1:1:3:3:5:5:5 ratio
2. Images created by artificial intelligence, further modified. There are a total of twelve different images with an equal chance of being minted.
So in total there are 9x12 (108) different AI image x frame combinations.
However, due to different rarities, some are repeated more often, while the rarest ones have a chance of 1:300. Because of this, the total number to be minted is set at 600, giving some chance that the rarest combinations will also be minted.
Due to the uniqueness of the generated barcode, even iterations with the same combination of generated layers are not identical, but each one is unique.
In the lower right corner, below the barcode, the rarity calculation is displayed. Specifically, it is a calculation of the chance of minting a given combination. Not a rarity among already minted iterations.

Image resolution: 1760x2250px
You can download the PNG after pressing the "s" key.

The javascript source code is licensed under the MIT license.
